<div id="myTabContent" class="tab-content">
  <div class="tab-pane fade show active" style="background-color: var(--card-bg)" id="01" role="tabpanel">
    <h4>Master the fundamental laws of electricity to work on network and telecommunications equipment (AC11.01)</h4>
    <p> As part of the physical network audit, I had to work on active equipment (Cisco 2960 switches). <br> <br> I became aware of the electrical risks related to network and telecommunications equipment. My interventions were carried out safely during physical cabling tasks.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" style="background-color: var(--card-bg)" id="02" role="tabpanel">
    <h4>Understand digital systems architecture and information coding principles (AC11.02)</h4>
    <p> Securing access to company network equipment. <br> <br> I configured console line, privileged exec mode (enable), and virtual lines (VTY) passwords on the switches. I can identify the link between these different passwords and the corresponding access modes. <br> <br> Ultimately, all active equipment is secured and accessible remotely via the SSH protocol, in accordance with the specifications.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" style="background-color: var(--card-bg)" id="03" role="tabpanel">
    <h4>Configure basic local area network functions (AC11.03)</h4>
    <p>Simulation and extension of the local area network on Cisco Packet Tracer. <br> <br> IP Addressing: Configuration and justification of the IPv4 addressing plan (addresses, masks, gateways) for new workstations.<br> <br> VLANs: Creation and configuration of specific VLANs (VLAN 70 for production, 71 for sales, 72 for HR) in access and trunk modes. <br> <br>Ultimately resulting in a functional topology allowing traffic separation and dynamic addressing via a DHCP server.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" style="background-color: var(--card-bg)" id="04" role="tabpanel">
    <h4>Master the roles and fundamental principles of operating systems to interact with them for network and services configuration and administration (AC11.04)</h4>
    <p>Frame analysis and discovery of the existing topology. <br> <br> Frame Analysis: Using Wireshark to analyze ICMP, ARP, and CDP traffic to identify active IP addresses and infrastructure equipment. <br> <br>Topology: Autonomous identification of the logical and physical topology (links between S1, S4, and the router) from network captures and configuration files. <br> <br>Ultimately resulting in accurate network mapping without prior documentation.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" style="background-color: var(--card-bg)" id="05" role="tabpanel">
    <h4>Identify local area network malfunctions (AC11.05)</h4>
    <p>Resolving problems encountered during the implementation of the backup server.<br> <br> I conducted a preliminary study (topology, addressing plan) and used diagnostic tools (command lines, analyzers) to solve configuration errors independently.<br> <br> Ultimately resulting in the identification and correction of a Windows Firewall block on port 69, allowing TFTP transfers to function correctly.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" style="background-color: var(--card-bg)" id="06" role="tabpanel">
    <h4>Install a client workstation (AC11.06)</h4>
    <p>Installation and configuration of a TFTP server on a Windows administration workstation and installation of three client machines under Ubuntu.<br> <br> Installation of a client workstation with a correctly connected and usable TCP/IPv4 protocol. I was able to justify my installation choices, particularly for the Tftpd64 application and the necessary security exceptions. <br> <br>Ultimately resulting in an operational administration workstation capable of receiving and storing switch configuration files.</p>
  </div>
</div>
